{
  "texts": [
    "□Observe that for a genus 2 surface, we only obtain locally homogeneous solitons since N 0 or N 1 = N g-1 are the only components.",
    "However, as soon as the genus of B 2 is ≥ 3, we obtain infinite families of solitons that are not locally homogeneous.",
    "In fact, by allowing the conformal class c to vary, we have the following description, from which Corollary E follows easily.Taking a time derivative at t = 0 yields the static equation satisfied by affine expanding solitons:(26) Ric g +Hessf + 1 2 g = D V P P t 0.Here f: M → R is the N-invariant lift to M, D V ∈ End(V) inv is the invariant endomorphism corresponding to a derivation field D ad ∈ Γ Der(adM), and P: H → V is defined implicitly by g(P Y, U) = -g([X V, Y], U).",
    "The blocks in (26) are according to T M = V⊕H.",
    "If θ: T M → V is the connection form for H (see Section 2), then P is L X V θ restricted to H. (This is seen by applying L X V to 0 = θY, Y ∈ Γ(H).)"
  ]
}